# AWS Infrastructure Deployment via Custom Terraform Modules

This project demonstrates a modular approach to provisioning infrastructure on AWS using Terraform. Instead of writing monolithic configuration files, the architecture is split into a **root module** that orchestrates deployments and **child modules** dedicated to specific resource types (EC2 and S3).

## Project Architecture & Directory Structure

The project repository is structured as follows. It isolates the child module configurations within a dedicated directory (`own-terra-child-module-details`), keeping the root directory clean and maintainable.


.
├── main.tf                            # Root module: Instantiates the EC2 and S3 child modules
├── provide.tf                         # Root module: Defines the AWS provider configuration
├── terra.tf                           # Root module: Configures required providers and versions
├── terraform.tfstate                  # Local state file tracking deployed resources
└── own-terra-child-module-details    # Internal directory containing reusable child modules
    ├── ec2-own                        # Child module for EC2 compute provisioning
    │   ├── data.tf                    # Dynamically fetches the latest Ubuntu AMI
    │   └── main.tf                    # Declares EC2 resource, variables, and configurations
    └── s3-own                         # Child module for S3 storage provisioning
        └── main.tf                    # Declares random ID generator, S3 bucket, and outputs


## Detailed Task Breakdown & Implementation

### Task 1: Setup Core Infrastructure Components (Root Module)

The root module acts as the entry point. It configures the target AWS cloud provider, defines strict version constraints for stability, and calls our internal child modules.

#### `provide.tf`

Specifies the region where our infrastructure will be deployed.

```hcl
# Configure the default AWS Provider to target the Mumbai region
provider "aws" {
  region = "ap-south-1"
}

```

#### `terra.tf`

Locks down the specific provider versions to ensure configuration consistency across different environments.

```hcl
# Define provider requirements and source registries
terraform {
  required_providers {
    aws = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "6.41.0"
    }
    random = {
      source  = "hashicorp/random"
      version = "3.8.1"
    }
  }
}

```

#### `main.tf`

Instantiates both the S3 and EC2 local child modules.

```hcl
# Call the internal child module to provision the S3 storage stack
module "eco-s3" {
  source = "./own-terra-child-module-details/s3-own"
}

# Call the internal child module to provision the EC2 compute stack
module "eco-ec2" {
  source = "./own-terra-child-module-details/ec2-own"
}

```

